BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 144.72 740 Td (Chapter 3: Understanding Your Climate Zone) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (The USDA Hardiness Zone Map divides North America into 13 planting zones.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (Your zone number tells you the average minimum winter temperature in your area.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (Find your zone at planagrden.gov or on seed packet labels and plant tags.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Your zone determines which plants survive winter and when to plant each crop.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Frost dates are critical: last spring frost and first fall frost define your season.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (Search your city plus last frost date to find your specific dates online.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (Cool-season crops like lettuce and peas grow best in spring and fall.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Warm-season crops like tomatoes and peppers need soil above 60 degrees.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (Plant cool-season crops four to six weeks before the last frost date.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Plant warm-season crops two weeks after the last frost when soil is warm.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Your growing season length determines which varieties to choose.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (Short-season gardeners should select early-maturing varieties for best results.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 303.6 40 Td (3) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
