BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 175.44 740 Td (Chapter 4: Soil Preparation Basics) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (Good soil is the single most important factor in growing healthy vegetables.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (Ideal garden soil is dark, crumbly, and smells earthy and fresh.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (Most native soil needs improvement with organic matter before planting.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Compost is the best soil amendment: it improves drainage, nutrients, and structure.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Add two to four inches of compost to your bed and mix into the top eight inches.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (For raised beds, fill with a mix of topsoil, compost, and perlite.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (A soil test from your local extension office reveals pH and nutrient levels.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Most vegetables prefer slightly acidic to neutral soil with pH 6.0 to 7.0.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (Clay soil needs compost and sand to improve drainage and prevent waterlogging.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Sandy soil needs compost to improve water retention and nutrient holding.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Never work wet soil as this compacts it and destroys beneficial structure.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (Healthy soil is alive with billions of microorganisms that feed your plants.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 303.6 40 Td (4) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
