BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 140.88 740 Td (Chapter 6: Easiest Vegetables for Beginners) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (Lettuce and salad greens grow quickly, producing harvests in just 30 days.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (Radishes are the fastest vegetable: ready to eat in only 25 to 30 days.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (Cherry tomatoes are more forgiving than large tomatoes and produce abundantly.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Zucchini and summer squash grow vigorously and produce more than you can eat.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Green beans are nearly foolproof. Plant seeds directly after last frost.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (Cucumbers climb trellises saving space and produce heavily all summer.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (Herbs like basil, parsley, and cilantro grow easily in gardens or pots.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Peppers \(sweet and hot\) thrive in warm weather with minimal fuss.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (Kale is extremely hardy and produces leaves from spring through winter frost.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Garlic is planted in fall and requires almost zero care until summer harvest.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Start with three to five of these easy crops for your first garden season.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 436 Td (Success with easy crops builds confidence for more challenging vegetables later.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F1 10 Tf 303.6 40 Td (6) Tj ET

endstream
endobj
