BT 0 g /F2 16 Tf 202.32 740 Td (Chapter 13: When to Harvest) Tj ET
q 0 G 1 w 70 725 m 542 725 l S Q
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 700 Td (Harvest most vegetables when they are young and tender for best flavor.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 676 Td (Zucchini tastes best at six to eight inches. Large ones become tough and seedy.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 652 Td (Tomatoes are ready when fully colored and slightly soft to gentle pressure.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 628 Td (Pick beans when pods snap cleanly and before seeds bulge through the skin.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 604 Td (Lettuce can be harvested leaf by leaf or by cutting the whole head.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 580 Td (Cut-and-come-again lettuce regrows multiple harvests from one planting.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 556 Td (Carrots are ready when the top of the root is visible at the soil surface.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 532 Td (Peppers can be picked green for mild flavor or left to ripen for sweeter taste.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 508 Td (Cucumbers taste best picked young before seeds develop and skin toughens.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 484 Td (Herbs should be harvested regularly to encourage bushy growth and prevent bolting.) Tj ET
BT 0 g /F4 11 Tf 60 460 Td (Morning harvest after dew dries yields the crispest, most flavorful vegetables.) Tj ET
